PADDY PRODUCTION BEFORE AND AFTER BAN ON
asked the Minister of Agriculture and Plantation Industries:
(a) Will he inform this House, separately based on each year -
(i) the annual paddy harvest of Sri Lanka in metric tons in the five years immediately prior to the year in which the use of chemical fertilizer was banned and organic farming was introduced;
(ii) the expenditure borne on the importation of the chemical fertilizer during the said period; and
(iii) the extent of land in which paddy was cultivated during the above period?
(b) Will he also inform this House, separately based on each year -
(i) the annual paddy harvest from the year in which organic fertilizer was introduced to date;
(ii) the expenditure borne on the importation of organic fertilizer during the said period;
(iii) the increase or the decrease of the paddy production as a percentage, prior to and subsequent to the ban imposed on the use of chemical fertilizer; and
(iv) the increase or the decrease of the land extent used for paddy cultivation as a percentage, prior and subsequent to the ban imposed on the use of fertilizer?
(c) Will he further inform this House of the measures that have been taken to promote paddy cultivation?
(d) If not, why? ( ) ( - ) (The Hon. Mahinda Amaraweera- Minister of Agriculture and Plantation Industries) , .

, , - Ministry of Ports, Shipping and Aviation .

Speaking on the Votes of the Ministry of Ports, Shipping and Aviation, I would like to urge the Government to look at the option of bringing in small aircraft which can land at the domestic airports we already have in the country. I know that the President has proposed to construct an international airport in Hingurakgoda. I am not opposed to that, but I do not know how practical it is because we already have two international airports in this country and whether that is the best option. Actually, right now, we have three international airports including the one in Jaffna. So, the international airport in Hingurakgoda would be the fourth. But, I think what we should look at is, at least, expanding the Jaffna International Airport. Its runway needs to be expanded from the northern side and I do not think there is any issue of it being expanded. When we spoke with the President, we raised this matter, but to date, there has been no progress on that. Even to the District of Batticaloa, there is a possibility of bringing in 40-seater or 45-seater aircraft. Therefore, we need to speak to companies which run small light aircraft services and ask them to come and invest in this country because we need to create more connectivity. If we have a domestic flight from Batticaloa to Colombo, people can catch an international flight from Colombo to their final destination. That might be a better solution because building a fourth international airport may take quite a bit of time. Even the hoteliers in Pasikudah and Trincomalee are suffering because - if I am not mistaken, when lands were given in Pasikudah, they were asked to build hotels immediately - we have a large number of hotels built in Pasikudah, but we see that their occupancy is very less. So, without improving connectivity, I do not think we will have tourists coming in to places like Batticaloa.
( ) (The Hon. Presiding Member) Hon. Member, please wind up now.
( ) (The Hon. Shanakiyan Rajaputhiran Rasamanickam) I am winding up, Sir.
Finally, I think the ferry service that is operating there right now has temporarily been suspended and will restart

in January. I was told that it was due to the weather or the monsoon season, of which I am not too sure. I think the Talaimannar-Rameswaram ferry service is a more practical option. I was told that it is 56 nautical miles from KKS Port to the Karaikal Port, but it is only 18 nautical miles from Talaimannar to Rameswaram. So, you can reduce the duration of the journey from three hours to one hour. So, that should be taken into consideration because that will change the prices as well.
( ) (The Hon. Presiding Member) Hon. Member, your time is over. Please wind up.
( ) (The Hon. Shanakiyan Rajaputhiran Rasamanickam) I am winding up, Sir.

So, please look into those serious issues. Ports and aviation is a very important aspect and the Trincomalee Harbour also needs to be developed. In the interest of time, I will wind up my speech. The Minister is not here. Ah, he just walked in. Hon. Minister, if you could please respond to the matters about the Airport in Jaffna, the runway of which needs expansion from the northern side, having an airline with light aircraft which operates domestically and also the the use of the Talaimannar-Rameswaram ferry service, which is a journey of only 18 nautical miles, that would be appreciated.

, . , , . , . SAGT , . . . . , . . . That is called the Concession Agreement. There is a particular clause in that to set up a Port Regulator. Now, that is very important. , . CICT , SAGT , East Container Terminal , West Container Terminal .

Then, you are talking about a North Terminal. When all these terminals come up - already there is heavy competition - that competition will become more pronounced. You have reached a compromise with the Adani Group on the so-called agreement to start their new terminal - the West Container Terminal. Once it begins to operate, that competition will be even more pronounced; with that competition, there will be a price war. With that price war, there will be a serious problem, particularly for the SLPA-managed terminals. Already, the JCT is in trouble. Even with regard to the East Container Terminal, though we fought and took it, you are still to begin the work. You have now imported the cranes and those cranes will be operational, maybe, towards the end of next year. So, by the time you start that terminal, you will have a serious price war because by the end of next year, Adanis will be ready to start work. They are starting work. With them, with the surplus capacity, there will be serious competition. So, that competition has to be regulated and we have to have a Port Regulator. Of course, this country has had a terrible experience with Regulators. Hon. Minister, you know what had happened with the other Regulator. - [Interruption.] No, the Public Utilities Commission. With all the public utilities, we have had problems. That is because, sometimes, the
Executive, for his own convenience, wants to bring pressure on the Regulator. That is not the way to go about it. So, with those issues, a Regulator is very important.

( ) (The Hon. Presiding Member) , . ( ) (The Hon. Rauff Hakeem, Attorney-at-Law) There would be a serious problem when the Vizhinjam Port in Kerala, next to Thiruvananthapuram, comes up. They are having a collaboration with MSC. There are about six major shipping lines and MSC is one of the leading shipping lines. When MSC will have a joint venture - with regard to Mundra Port, they have a joint venture - there will be a conflict of interest and we will have a problem because they will be owning these ports. Of course, we need to develop our ports, have PPP investments, but we need to be very cautious and see that our competitiveness in the Port of Colombo is preserved. The sum total of all the terminals is the Port of Colombo. So, the Port of Colombo's competitiveness will have to be preserved. To preserve that, I think we have to have a Regulator fast and I hope the Hon. Minister will take action to appoint a Port Regulator very soon.
With that, I will make one final comment. The Oluvil Port has a serious problem with the port mouth being blocked by sand that is getting collected there.
( ) (The Hon. Rauff Hakeem, Attorney-at-Law) Thank you very much, Sir.

The Danish company that developed the Oluvil Port has promised about US Dollars 12 million as compensation, but there has been no attempt to take that compensation because they say, they need about US Dollars 20 million. So, please look into that, see that you get the compensation and address those issues with regard to the Oluvil Port.
